@P4newstreet @Elwick70 That range is -18°C to +38°C air temperature. Above that range, the balance weight stacks that provide the tension on both systems can bottom out, resulting in lower tension and excessive sag.

@P4newstreet @Elwick70 👋 overhead line engineer here, sorry to butt in. Just want to clear up a few misconceptions. Both the east coast and west coast systems are auto tensioned, such that the amount of sag between structures is constant *within the design temperature range of the system*.

If you want to know more about how BT/RC feeding works, why it was needed at all and why it is no longer in favour in the UK, read my proper thread here: https://t.co/xo7oHESAZf

Why did it fail? I don't know. Possible causes are failure of a splice (https://t.co/XK0F4pXUMg section 12.17.1), burning of the wire due to a bird or debris shorting it to earth, or mechanical fatigue failure. The conductor is aluminium so corrosion shouldn't be an issue

Even though this is the "earthed" half of the circuit, cutting a circuit always leads to a rise in voltage - which is why you should never touch a broken bond on site, or a loose neutral wire in your house.
Why is there a voltage on the RC at all? It is part of the traction return system - the part of the circuit that returns current from the train to the power supply.

That's plenty enough to kill a track worker by direct contact, or nearby member of public without direct contact. How? The voltage gradient in the surrounding ground will create a small voltage between your two feet. This could drive enough current through your heart to kill you https://t.co/7TrQG0O4Lw

It should absolutely not be lying on the ground - it should be up where the dotted line is. The cable has failed and fallen to ground level. Why is this bad news? If an electric train is in section, there will be a dangerous voltage on this conductor. It could easily be > 1000V

What's wrong with this picture? Well, the conductor that is arrowed is a Return Conductor (RC). It is part of the Booster Transformer (BT) / RC feeding system that is installed on the Cross City line, as well as almost all OLE systems lines installed in UK between 1960 and 2010. https://t.co/ModrW0CaY3

Now this railway has a passing place about half way up. But a horizontal rack is incompatible with conventional switch and crossings. So how is it done?

Simple! Replace the whole track section with another one! https://t.co/vV1XcQFcnD

So the railway has a horizontal dual faced rack and trains have 2 cogs that suit either side and grip the rack. https://t.co/x4zSNMRWKF
A normal rack railway uses a vertically mounted cog/rack. But at these gradients that would spell disaster - traction forces would push the cog out and you'd have a spectacular runaway train.

The mechanical engineering here is incredible. This entire assembly isn't supporting the cable - it's holding it down; all those wheels are spreading the radial force created by the high tension cable changing direction from horizontal to inclined, and directing it into the pylon https://t.co/ib2v78WI7S
Then the Big Clock grabs the car and supports it as it pulls around 180 degrees. Then the whole thing happens again in reverse before it begins its next journey https://t.co/shYxCDXLKE

I spent a bit of time at the bottom trying to understand how it all works. The upper rail presses on the lever which releases the cable clamp (how is that done safely?), then the lower rail lifts the car away from the cable, while the tyres slow it down. https://t.co/N03ErXHiRU
